snippet.text: Before its tenure as a federal penitentiary from 1934 to 1963, Alcatraz operated as a U.S. Army military prison. Alcatraz housed roughly 1,500 prisoners, such as Al Capone and Robert Franklin Stroud, aka "Birdman". Thirty-six prisoners tried to escape from Alcatraz over the course of 29 years.

This past weekend I visited Alcatraz for the first time to see @Large, an exhibition of work by Ai Weiwei, a Chinese artist and political activist. Unable to leave his own country, Ai developed the entire exhibition from his studio in Beijing and remotely directed the installation of his art throughout three of the buildings on the island. The powerful message of Ai's work presented among the historical ruins of Alcatraz made this an overwhelmingly epic experience. I highly recommend you see it for yourself...

Last month we stayed in San Francisco for a few days, as the start of our longer trip through California. It was such an inspiring stay! San Francisco and surrounding area has so much to offer; beautiful Victorian architecture, lovely shops and restaurants, stunning redwoods and a vibrant coffee scene. What else do we need?

This weekend a few of my closest friends and I wandered around Lands End, San Francisco. We were greeted by warm sunny weather, misty air, and lots of good picnicking spots. First stop the abandoned Sutro Baths: Once the largest covered swimming pool in the late 19th century, the baths went bankrupt and burned down, leaving concrete ruins behind.

Nowhere in my life have I ever connected and felt at home the instant my feet touched ground like I did in San Francisco. It took hold of me and I couldn't and still can't get it out of my head .
